</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DA60615B05E9B6256AA306F966B420DE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="5B35B0E4D456B8377C44027331FEF6F7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="09BF44859EE79DA9B9198BCCA6EB3505" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="1574425E46816BF10E05EA85C444291B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chiquitensis">
<emphasis id="89DDCE925FF0770DD3A62BE5BDBCECF9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea chiquitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinctive species readily recognised by the very small, shortly pedunculate flowers, adaxially pilose leaves and small pointed pilose sepals. The small glabrous pink corolla (c. 2.2 cm long) is only matched by that of 
<taxonomicName id="9069B63970D6DF49298937E3046090C0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumetorum">
<emphasis id="3C23689A3DC68E7DBB00C1DF5F2FD634" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. dumetorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DE1BFCA38CD5FF079DE080D811BE6BA3" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deminuta">
<emphasis id="5BC54A94BD729B96BDB89F54BFCEA514" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. deminuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some species in the 
<taxonomicName id="ADA5B42BC8EBDC112C4730F443E0E6F1" authority="" authorityName="" class="Liliopsida" family="Eriospermaceae" genus="Batatas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Batatas</taxonomicName>
Clade (A3), such as 
<taxonomicName id="BA9C03858E622AE2E91EF4A6C63B6B27" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramosissima">
<emphasis id="52FE7EC7A138A0C571FACEFBAE166005" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. ramosissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is readily distinguished from all of these by the distinctive ovate, acute sepals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
